courses.learning_outcomes:
Upon completion of the course, students will be able to:

1. to identify grammatical properties of Chinese and English in a linguistically informed manner;
2. to describe and compare the similarities and differences between Chinese and English without prejudice;
3. to synthesize the principles of comparative grammar learned in this course and theorize about the linguistic facts; and

4. to develop sustained interest in further pursuing some of the linguistic issues arisen from comparative grammar.

Upon completion of the course, students will be able to:
(a) A clear understanding of the basic units and categories of language; morpheme, root, stem, affix, word and compound; dilatational morphology and inflectional morphology as well as prosodic morphology; an ability to define these units and categories, and justify why particular form (bound or free forms) belong to them;
(b) The ability to describe the structure of word-formation of certain forms in a language, and respond to the definitions define them;
(c) An understanding of the standard judgments for what is a word and what is a phrase and the complexity to define specific cases such as "phrasal word", "prosodically bound and syntactically free"
(d) An interest to observe the languages encountered in daily life, and some skills in tapping into one's own native language competence;
(e) A sensitivity to the possibility of alternative analyses for the same morphological phenomena, and an elementary grasp of the methodological reasons for favoring one analysis over another, with reference to criteria such as economy, internal consistency, pattern congruity, productivity, linguistically significant generalizations and learnability;
(f) Some familiarity with the standard Chinese linguistics terms used for basic morphological concepts in general linguistics.
